  "articleSummary": "The article argues that fixed dropdown priority fields (e.g., P1–P4, Low–Critical) in project management tools like Jira inevitably lead to \"Engineering Theater,\" where teams invent ever-higher priorities (P0, P00) to accommodate shifting demands, creating an unmanageable backlog. It criticizes this binary approach and recommends unbounded numeric ranges, multidimensional scoring, or methods like MoSCoW and the Kano Model. The tone is satirical and analytical, using metaphors such as a \"z-index war\" to illustrate the inflation of priority levels. The intended audience is software teams, Jira admins, and product managers dealing with backlog bloat.",
